english:
  title: 'Epitaph and Preface for Minister Min Je of Yeohung, Posthumously Titled Mundu: Grand Commandant and Mentor of State, Senior Mentor of崇祿, Minister of the Bureau of Rites, and Compiler of the Sects of Literature'
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Minister Min bore the family name Min, with personal name Je and courtesy name Jung-hoe; his literary name was Eoan. He came from the great family of Yeohung. His great-grandfather, whose name was Jong-yu, served the Mighty King of Goryeo as Councilor of State and received the posthumous title Chung-sun. Chung-sun fathered his grandfather, who held the position of Director of the Secretariat and bore the posthumous title Mun-sun. Mun-sun fathered his father, the Grand Commandant Lord of Yeohung, whose name was Pyeon. His father married the daughter of Lord Heo Baek-ji, who held the rank of Vice-Director of the Eastern Expeditionary Chancellery and received the posthumous title Mun-jung, thus Min Je was born.

    From childhood, the Minister showed brilliance surpassing all others. Whatever books he read, he could retain with a single glance. He was especially skilled in historical studies. In the year Jeong-yu of Zhizheng, at the age of nineteen, he passed the civil service examination and was appointed Instructor of the National Academy. In Imsin year, he was selected to enter the Hall of Literary Excellence. The following year he became Ceremony Master. In Byeong-o year he was transferred to Vice-Director of Records. In the Xinhai year of Hongwu, he was promoted to Director of Rites. In Imja year, he moved to Senior Director of Records and Editor of Imperial Edicts. In Gyechuk year he was elevated to Examiner of the National Academy. In Eulmo year he became Senior Master of Ceremonies. The following year he transferred to the Military Records Bureau. In the seventh year of Xuanguang, he became Director of the National Academy. In Imseul year of Hongwu, he became Judge of the Bureau of Records. In Jeongmyo year, he went out as magistrate of Chunju, where he brought benevolent governance to the people. The following year he became Judge of the Minor Administration Bureau and Compiler of the Hall of Literary Excellence, holding the rank of Court Attendant. In the eighth month he was transferred to Senior Minister of Works. Shortly after, he became Minister of Rites and concurrent knowledge of the Historiography Bureau, serving as Commander. In the summer of Gisa year, he transferred to the Ministry of Lands. In the seventh month, he again moved to the Records Bureau. In the ninth month he became Administrator of Kaesong and councilor in the Secretariat, concurrently Minister of Rites. The following year he became Concurrent Vice-Director of the Secretariat and concurrent Vice-President of the State Council, keeping his ranks as before, and also became Left Attendant of the Crown Prince. In Imsin year he went out as Administrator of Hanyang. In the seventh month, when our Great Founder established the Dynasty, he was appointed Senior Commandant, Compiler of both the Hall of Literary Excellence and the Historiography Bureau. In Gapsin year, he was transferred to Chamberlain of the Palace and concurrent Vice-President of the State Council, becoming Scholar of the Hall of Literary Excellence. In winter, he served as Envoy to the Ming Court bearing congratulations. Upon his return, he became Vice-Minister of the Three Excellencies and Director of the Hall of Literary Excellence. In Muin year, autumn, he received promotion to Senior Minister. Soon after, he was appointed Special Commandant, Grand Mentor of State, and Lord of Yeohung, serving as Director of the Bureau of Rites and concurrent Judge of the Bureaus of Ritual and Agriculture, Scholar of the Hall of Literary Excellence.

    Since the Minister had been known for his knowledge of propriety from youth, from his appointment to the Three Excellencies to this rank of Grand Mentor, he also served concurrently in the Bureau of Rites. In Gimi year of Jianwen, he served as Director of the Civil Service Examination. That winter he became Vice-Minister of the Three Excellencies. In the second month of Gyeongsin year, when the Crown Prince became what would be the Great Progenitor, the Yuan-敬 Queen was elevated to Honored Consort. In the third month, he received court rank as Distinguished Commandant for Assisting Succession, appointed Right Premier of the State Council, Judge of the State Council, Minister of War, concurrent Judge of the Court of Imperial Insignia, Scholar of the Hall of Literary Excellence, Supervisor of both the Hall of Literary Excellence and Historiography Bureau, and Controller of the Lecture Hall, enfeoffed as Lord of Yeohung. In the fourth month he received the new title of Co-Virtuous Assistant to Mandate. He also took charge of recording the great affairs of state and military. In the ninth month he was transferred to Left Premier. In the eleventh month, when the Great Progenitor ascended the throne, the Yuan-敬 Queen was elevated to Principal Consort. The title Pure Loyalty was bestowed, and he remained enfeoffed as Lord of Yeohung. In Sinsa year, he received the title Pure Loyalty and Co-Virtuous Assistant to Succession and Transformation of Merit, and was enfeoffed as Duke.

    In the ninth month of Muja year of Yongle, the Minister fell ill. When his illness became critical, the Great Progenitor himself visited his residence to inquire after his health. The Minister adjusted his robes and cap, and his words flowed as if in ordinary times. Three days later, he passed away at the age of seventy. When the report of his death reached the court, the Great Progenitor was deeply grieved, suspended court sessions, and personally came to offer sacrifices. The Bureau of Ritual gave him the posthumous title Mundu. In the eleventh month of that year, the competent authorities conducted ceremonies and buried him in Jungnyeon-ri of Haepung County.

    The Minister possessed a temperate and benevolent nature, was clear-minded and simple in his ways. He devoted himself to the classics and histories, paid little attention to acquiring household property, and disdained ostentation. He opposed heterodox teachings and despised spurious religious practices. He had artisans paint on walls images of servants wielding staves and setting dogs upon monks and sorceresses, and of medicines curing the ailments of people and beasts, that others might observe them. When our Great Founder reformed private landholding, the Minister took charge of establishing the system of official land distribution. Upon the founding of the Dynasty, when the Institutions of Statecraft in Six Sections was compiled, the Minister detailed all the great and small rites and ceremonies of the nation. He supervised the establishment of both the old and new capitals, military camps, and the Confucian Temple. Though the Minister rose to the highest honors and ranks, he showed not the slightest appearance of wealth or status. Daily he amused himself with the game of go and board games, excelled in the evaluation of poetry, and possessed a refined detachment from worldly concerns. He often admonished his sons Mugo and Muil, saying: "If you do not correct your arrogance, you shall surely be destroyed." Thus the Minister's knowledge of his sons was truly penetrating.

    His wife, Lady Song, came from the prominent family of Yeosan. She was the great-granddaughter of Minister Song Yeom of the Ministry of Records, granddaughter of Administrator Song Hun, and daughter of Grand Commandant Lord of Yeosan, Song Seon. She was generous and virtuous, diligent and frugal, and governed her household with proper method. In Muin year of Hongwu, she was enfeoffed as Grand Lady of the Korean Kingdom. In Elyou year of Yongle, she was elevated to Grand Lady of the Three Han Kingdoms. In the sixth month of Gapsin year, she died of illness at the age of eighty-three. When word of her death reached the court, the ruler donned mourning garments, led the hundred officials in raising laments, and after six days personally attended the rites, sending an envoy to present offerings. In the eighth month of that year, they were buried together in Jungnyeon-ri.

    The Grand Lady bore four sons and three daughters. Our Yuan-敬 Queen Mother was the second daughter. The Grand Lady's eldest son was Mugo, followed by Muil, Muhye, and Muhoe. All three of these sons died in exile as punishment for their crimes, preceding the Grand Lady in death. The eldest daughter married Cho Pok, and the youngest daughter married No Hae.

    Mugo married the daughter of Gwon Hyeon, Censor of Rank, and fathered son Chu. Muil married the daughter of Han Sang-hwan, former Administrator of Seoul, and fathered three sons—Chuk, Sam, and Bun—and two daughters. The eldest daughter married former Minister Kim Young-ryun and bore one son, still young. The second daughter married Scholar Yi Gin and bore one son and two daughters, all young. The third daughter married Scholar Hong Woo-myeong. Muhye married the daughter of Duke Lee Jik of Sungsan and fathered four daughters. The eldest married Scholar Song Jun, and the second married Scholar Kim Yang-jung and bore two daughters, still young. Muhoe married the daughter of Vice-Minister Kim Ik-dal and fathered one son and one daughter. The son Rui is still young; the daughter married Scholar Kim Chi. Cho Pok fathered one son and one daughter. The son Shin-eon married the daughter of Bang Gan and fathered two sons and one daughter. The sons Neul and Muk are still young; the daughter married Scholar Park Sa-hyeon. No Hae fathered one son and two daughters. The son Mul-jae married the daughter of Sim On and fathered two sons, both still young. The eldest daughter married Lee Jong-in and bore two sons and two daughters, all young. The second daughter married Choi Hu, Vice-Prefect of Insu, and bore three sons and one daughter, all young.

    Alas! The Minister and the Grand Lady, with all their extended family, together formed a luminous great house of the realm. Through the accumulation of virtue and the cultivation of merit, they produced our Yuan-敬 Queen Mother, who became the consort of the sovereign and mother of the realm, bearing the holy heir who continued the great succession and opened infinite blessings for ten thousand generations. How glorious this is! How could one as crude and unskilled in letters as this minister dare to wield the brush of the inner chamber to describe even one ten-thousandth of their glory? Yet taking upon myself the duty of historian and humbly receiving the sovereign's command, I dare not decline through lack of eloquence.

    Herewith I have extracted the essentials of the Minister's genealogy, official career, and deeds, and composed this epitaph:

    The ancestors of this Lord
    Dug deep the source of virtue;
    Generation succeeded generation
    In transmitting excellence to their descendants.

    Lord Mundu further expanded
    The glory of his house;
    The admirable Lady was
    The model of all wives.

    The blessings of accumulated goodness
    Concentrated in her noble virtue;
    Raised to be the sovereign's companion,
    She became the mother of all people.

    She bore the sage child
    Who increased the luster of ancestral merit.
    Both before and after with imperial presence,
    Whose honor can compare?

    Behold the grave at Jungnyeon-ri:
    The hills embrace and the vital forces converge.
    The posthumous title bestowed by the throne is Mundu,
    Father of the Imperial Consort.

    The historian takes up his brush
    To illuminate the hidden chamber;
    With reverent obeisance, the words are inscribed
    Upon the stone for all ages.
    Through ten thousand years,
    May this glory endure without end.
  footnotes:
    - The Yuan-敬 Queen Mother (元敬王太后) was Minister Min Je's daughter who became the consort of King Taejong and bore King Sejong the Great.
    - The 'Three Han Kingdoms' (三韓) is a classical reference to the three ancient Korean kingdoms, used honorifically to refer to the entire Korean realm.
    - Jungnyeon-ri of Haepung County was the burial site, suggesting a place of auspicious geomantic significance.
    - The biographical form of epitaph (墓誌銘) was a standard literary genre during the Goryeo and early Joseon periods, combining genealogical record with eulogy.
